1
00:05:10,040 --> 00:05:12,031
<i>Our hero grew apace.</i>

2
00:05:12,160 --> 00:05:16,278
<i>A country lad, far happier
in the woods than in the study.</i>

3
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:19,597
<i>A bad hero, it may be,
with many a weakness.</i>

4
00:05:19,720 --> 00:05:22,871
<i>But then, if Adam hadn't had
such a weakness for apples,</i>

5
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,231
<i>there would be nobody
to tell Tom's story at all.</i>

6
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:31,150
<i>And a part of that story tells
of the sport Tom found in the woods.</i>

7
00:05:39,640 --> 00:05:41,790
Ah, Tom.

8
00:05:45,040 --> 00:05:46,996
You wicked dog.

9
00:05:47,120 --> 00:05:49,475
Molly. What are you doing here?

10
00:05:49,600 --> 00:05:52,751
I 'eard Father tell Mother
you was coming.

11
00:06:12,320 --> 00:06:15,995
It's a good night to be abroad
and looking for game.

12
00:06:16,120 --> 00:06:18,076
Ah, Tom...

13
00:06:22,720 --> 00:06:24,676
Oh, Tom...

14
00:06:37,360 --> 00:06:39,874
<i>It shall be our custom
to leave such scenes</i>

15
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:43,436
<i>where taste, decorum
and the censor dictate.</i>

16
00:06:44,680 --> 00:06:48,753
<i>In this way, we shall try to make up
for our incorrigible hero.</i>

17
00:06:50,480 --> 00:06:53,278
<i>As soon as he had left
the disreputable Molly,</i>

18
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:59,077
<i>what did he do but join her equally
disreputable father, Black George,</i>

19
00:06:59,200 --> 00:07:02,078
<i>gamekeeper to Squire Allworthy.</i>

20
00:07:06,720 --> 00:07:10,030
- Come on!
- I hear 'em. Psst.

21
00:07:11,080 --> 00:07:12,957
Come on, lads. We'll smoke 'em out.

22
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:15,958
Fetch it. Fetch it, boy. Come on.

23
00:07:16,080 --> 00:07:19,231
Wait. That's fallen
on Squire Western's ground.

24
00:07:19,360 --> 00:07:20,713
Well, let's after it.

25
00:07:20,840 --> 00:07:23,308
No - I've been warned for trespassing.

26
00:07:23,440 --> 00:07:25,556
It's our bird. Don't worry, Blackie.

27
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:29,434
- Come back! Come...
- Here, boy. Here, boy. Here, boy.

28
00:07:30,760 --> 00:07:33,399
All right, you devils, I'll get you!

29
00:07:34,240 --> 00:07:37,391
- I'll have your blood! I'll...
- Run, Blackie!

30
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:41,673
Let's give the old man
a run for his money.

31
00:07:56,600 --> 00:08:00,070
Home, lads. I'll get 'em another night.

32
00:08:01,880 --> 00:08:04,599
- I thought I'd lost you in the woods.
- Short cut.

33
00:08:04,720 --> 00:08:07,188
- We'll be caught one of these days.
- Don't worry.

34
00:08:07,320 --> 00:08:10,551
It's all right for you -
you haven't got a family to keep.

35
00:08:10,680 --> 00:08:13,194
<i>I'll look after you.</i>

36
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:16,278
Here... Take this guinea.

37
00:08:17,200 --> 00:08:19,156
Good night, Blackie.

38
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:24,879
<i>Our hero, alas, was always being
exploited by villains like Black George.</i>

39
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:30,313
<i>For a generous man is merely
a fool in the eyes of a thief.</i>

40
00:08:36,480 --> 00:08:39,233
<i>- A sheep?
- Aye, sir, an entire sheep.</i>

41
00:08:39,360 --> 00:08:42,750
A fat animal. Enough
to feed a village for a week.

42
00:08:42,880 --> 00:08:46,156
Hanging up in his cottage
as proud as a battle trophy.

43
00:08:46,280 --> 00:08:48,840
- This is a grave matter.
- A hanging matter.

44
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:53,078
- Sir, if I may speak on his behalf, I'd...
- Be silent.

45
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:55,912
Are you guilty?

46
00:08:56,040 --> 00:08:57,951
I am... guilty...

47
00:08:58,080 --> 00:09:01,755
- Sir, forgive him.
- Be quiet, sir. I have to do justice here.

48
00:09:02,240 --> 00:09:04,515
You have committed a capital crime.

49
00:09:04,640 --> 00:09:09,270
The laws have provided the most terrible
To hang by your neck.

50
00:09:11,040 --> 00:09:12,837
But you have children.

51
00:09:12,960 --> 00:09:16,873
For their sake, I shall only
dismiss you from my service.

52
00:09:17,160 --> 00:09:19,754
And may God have mercy on you.

53
00:09:21,280 --> 00:09:22,952
You're too lenient, Mr Allworthy.

54
00:09:23,080 --> 00:09:26,709
Compassion is one thing, sir,
but justice is another.

55
00:09:29,040 --> 00:09:32,555
<i>Mr Thwackum and Mr Square
were Tom's tutors.</i>

56
00:09:34,840 --> 00:09:37,593
<i>Over the years, they tried -
with little success -</i>

57
00:09:37,720 --> 00:09:40,917
<i>to thrash into Tom
a sense of virtue and religion.</i>

58
00:09:41,040 --> 00:09:43,873
<i>They had, however, a more apt pupil.</i>

59
00:09:44,760 --> 00:09:46,432
<i>Soon after Tom had been found,</i>

60
00:09:46,560 --> 00:09:50,792
<i>the squire's sister Bridget married
a Captain Blifil, and they had a son.</i>

61
00:09:50,920 --> 00:09:53,150
<i>This young man was
quite different from Tom.</i>

62
00:09:53,280 --> 00:09:56,477
<i>He was sober, discreet
and pious beyond his age,</i>

63
00:09:56,600 --> 00:10:00,115
<i>and the whole neighbourhood
resounded in his praise.</i>

64
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:04,992
You have only taught Tom to laugh at
whatever is decent and virtuous and right.

65
00:10:05,120 --> 00:10:09,033
- I've taught him religion.
- Mr Thwackum, the word "religion"

66
00:10:09,160 --> 00:10:12,232
is as vague and uncertain
as any in the English language.

67
00:10:12,360 --> 00:10:16,399
By "religion" I mean the Christian religion.
Not only that, but the Protestant religion.

68
00:10:16,520 --> 00:10:18,750
And not only that,
but the Church of England.

69
00:10:18,880 --> 00:10:21,758
I fear that Tom is the embodiment
of the old truth

70
00:10:21,880 --> 00:10:24,599
that foundlings
should be left to the parish.

71
00:10:24,720 --> 00:10:28,474
My dear tutors, I'm afraid neither of you
can touch his bastard's heart.

72
00:10:28,600 --> 00:10:32,718
<i>Neither indeed.
But there was another who could.</i>

73
00:10:39,520 --> 00:10:41,988
<i>Tom...</i>

74
00:10:42,120 --> 00:10:44,554
- I want you to help me.
- How?

75
00:10:45,160 --> 00:10:47,720
I want you to get me a post, Tom.

76
00:10:49,080 --> 00:10:51,116
Mm-hm...

77
00:10:51,240 --> 00:10:55,756
Miss Western's come back from France
and'll be wantin' a maid.

78
00:10:55,880 --> 00:10:58,348
I'll speak to her.

79
00:10:59,440 --> 00:11:01,635
Tom, you are kind to me.

80
00:11:07,160 --> 00:11:09,116
Miss Western's maid!

81
00:11:22,920 --> 00:11:25,957
Sophie Western! Miss Western!

82
00:11:26,640 --> 00:11:27,959
Why, Tom Jones!

83
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:30,355
I've brought you a thrush.

84
00:11:35,040 --> 00:11:38,112
He's beautiful, Tom. How kind of you.

85
00:11:38,400 --> 00:11:44,032
Two years is a long time. Did they teach
you London ways, make a lady of you?

86
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:46,720
Most of the time I was in France.
My aunt took me there.

87
00:11:46,840 --> 00:11:50,276
<i>- Did you like France, Meez Western?
- Mais oui. Je me suis très bien amusée.</i>

88
00:11:50,400 --> 00:11:52,868
<i>- Ah, bon.
- You haven't changed, Tom.</i>

89
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:56,390
You've grown, Sophie.
Grown more beautiful than ever.

90
00:11:58,520 --> 00:12:01,512
Doesn't he sing beautifully?
I shall teach him some new songs.

91
00:12:01,640 --> 00:12:04,359
I doubt if an English bird
can learn French songs.

92
00:12:04,480 --> 00:12:05,674
You'll see.

93
00:12:05,800 --> 00:12:07,472
<i>Avignon</i>

94
00:12:07,600 --> 00:12:10,990
<i>Sur le pont d'Avignon...</i>

95
00:12:14,040 --> 00:12:18,079
We're asked to supper. I came early to ask
if you'd help Black George's daughter.

96
00:12:18,200 --> 00:12:20,555
Oh, yes. He stole a sheep, didn't he?

97
00:12:20,680 --> 00:12:22,511
Black George is a poor man.

98
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:26,519
With big, hungry daughters to feed.
Most hungry - I can vouch for it.

99
00:12:26,640 --> 00:12:29,108
I have a maid already.
But I'll see what I can do.

100
00:12:29,240 --> 00:12:30,150
Good, good.

101
00:12:35,040 --> 00:12:38,476
Ah! Welcome, neighbours! Welcome!

102
00:12:38,600 --> 00:12:42,878
- How nice to see you.
- Welcome, madam. Welcome, Squire.

103
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:45,036
Good day, Western, good day.

104
00:12:45,160 --> 00:12:47,993
- Look! Tom brought me a thrush!
- What a sweet little bird!

105
00:12:48,120 --> 00:12:50,395
His song is sweeter
than any tune of Mr Handel's.

106
00:12:50,520 --> 00:12:52,590
Ugh, Handel!

107
00:12:53,520 --> 00:12:55,476
Tom, thank you.

108
00:12:56,280 --> 00:12:59,670
Welcome home, Sophie.
How lovely you're looking, child.

109
00:12:59,800 --> 00:13:03,873
Aye, it's good to have her home.
Let's all go in to dinner.

110
00:13:05,880 --> 00:13:08,792
- Oh dear.
- Oh, my little bird!

111
00:13:16,160 --> 00:13:18,469
Don't worry, Sophie,
I'll get it back for you.

112
00:13:18,600 --> 00:13:21,194
- Tom...
- Good lad, Tom.

113
00:13:22,680 --> 00:13:24,989
Be careful, Tom! Tom, take care!

114
00:13:25,120 --> 00:13:27,076
- I'll wager he gets it.
- Take care.

115
00:13:27,200 --> 00:13:30,158
I am sorry to cause you this distress,
Miss Western.

116
00:13:30,280 --> 00:13:32,555
I did not think the bird would fly away.

117
00:13:32,680 --> 00:13:35,877
But I cannot help observing
that the idea of caged birds

118
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:39,151
is against the laws of nature.
Don't you agree, Mr Square?

119
00:13:40,600 --> 00:13:42,477
He's got him!

120
00:13:43,040 --> 00:13:44,314
Argh!

121
00:13:46,080 --> 00:13:50,676
He'll drown! Quick, pick him up!
Help him, someone!

122
00:13:50,800 --> 00:13:53,598
- Oh, Tom, you're soaked!
- Come on, lad, give me your hand.

123
00:13:53,720 --> 00:13:57,190
Damn me if I won't love the boy for this
as long as I have to live!

124
00:13:57,320 --> 00:13:58,958
Serves him right.

125
00:13:59,080 --> 00:14:01,036
And you, sir.

126
00:14:10,640 --> 00:14:14,428
<i>The weeks passed...
and Molly grew apace too.</i>

127
00:14:15,840 --> 00:14:20,231
Ah, you lazy slut, you!
Look at her, with that great belly on her!

128
00:14:21,080 --> 00:14:23,594
That I should have lived to see this day!

129
00:14:23,720 --> 00:14:27,838
You'd better have minded what the parson
said and not harkened after menfolks.

130
00:14:27,960 --> 00:14:30,155
She's the first of this family to be a whore!

131
00:14:30,280 --> 00:14:34,239
Mother, you yourself was brought to bed
with sister there a week after you married.

132
00:14:34,360 --> 00:14:36,954
Ah, but I were made an honest woman of.

133
00:14:37,080 --> 00:14:41,949
But you, you have to be doing with
gentlemen, don't you, you nasty slut, you!

134
00:14:42,080 --> 00:14:45,755
You will have a bastard!
And I defy anybody to say that of me.

135
00:14:45,880 --> 00:14:51,159
- My gentlemen'll look after me.
- Your gentlemen! Far from gentlemen!

136
00:14:51,280 --> 00:14:53,999
You lay off me, or I'll tell my gentlemen...

137
00:14:58,480 --> 00:15:01,040
<i>...if these be constantly applied,</i>

138
00:15:01,160 --> 00:15:05,551
And then, though we cannot
absolutely promise success,

139
00:15:05,680 --> 00:15:09,468
yet we may properly say with the apostle

140
00:15:09,600 --> 00:15:15,118
"What knowest thou, O wife,
whether thou shalt save thy husband?"

141
00:15:15,920 --> 00:15:19,390
And now, my dear brethren,
let us sing together the hymn

142
00:15:19,520 --> 00:15:22,512
"O God, Our Help in Ages Past. "

143
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:35,917
O God, our help in ages past

144
00:15:36,360 --> 00:15:41,514
Our hope for years to come...

145
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:46,675
<i>"Let dogs delight to bark and bite,
For God hath made them so. "</i>

146
00:15:46,800 --> 00:15:50,509
<i>"Let bears and lions growl and fight,
For 'tis their nature too. "</i>

147
00:15:50,640 --> 00:15:54,394
<i>"But, ladies, you should never let
Such angry passions rise. "</i>

148
00:15:54,520 --> 00:15:58,638
<i>"Your little hands were never made
To tear each other's eyes. "</i>

149
00:15:59,640 --> 00:16:01,551
There she is! Let's get at her!

150
00:16:02,480 --> 00:16:04,232
Let's thrash her!

151
00:16:04,360 --> 00:16:09,150
Don't want the likes of her in this village!
Won't have her mixing with us good folk!

152
00:16:09,280 --> 00:16:11,350
Take that, you hussy!

153
00:16:23,160 --> 00:16:25,958
I'll get you, Goody Brown,
you dirty old harridan!

154
00:16:59,120 --> 00:17:01,680
Oh, Tom... Please, Tom...

155
00:17:02,680 --> 00:17:04,989
Don't... Don't leave me, Tom.

156
00:17:11,080 --> 00:17:13,594
Slowly. Slowly.

157
00:17:58,800 --> 00:18:00,756
That filthy slut.

158
00:18:01,160 --> 00:18:03,515
Ah, good boy, good boy!

159
00:18:04,200 --> 00:18:06,509
He's a game lad, your Tom.

160
00:18:07,040 --> 00:18:10,794
So, the wench is having a bastard?

161
00:18:10,920 --> 00:18:16,677
Yes. It seems the girl has refused
to name the father to Mr Allworthy.

162
00:18:17,880 --> 00:18:20,599
He may have to send her to Bridewell.

163
00:18:21,160 --> 00:18:24,118
- Father, I have a headache.
- I smoke it.

164
00:18:26,560 --> 00:18:30,269
I smoke it!
Tom is the father of that bastard!

165
00:18:32,400 --> 00:18:36,234
Aye! As sure as tuppence,
Tom is the bastard's father!

166
00:18:36,360 --> 00:18:37,110
Father...

167
00:18:37,240 --> 00:18:41,279
Odds zodikins!
What a little whoremaster that boy is!

168
00:18:41,400 --> 00:18:43,595
The girl is ruined, surely.

169
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:48,396
Aye! Ruined. Ruined for sure!
Once broken, never mended, eh?

170
00:18:57,400 --> 00:19:02,110
Lt'll do no harm. Ask Sophie.
She knows about Tom.

171
00:19:03,080 --> 00:19:07,517
You have no worse opinion of a young
fellow for getting a bastard, have you?

172
00:19:07,640 --> 00:19:10,393
Will you stop bobbing up and down, girl!

173
00:19:10,840 --> 00:19:15,231
No, no. The women will like him
the better for it, won't they?

174
00:19:17,560 --> 00:19:22,236
- Sophie, sing us one of your jolly songs.
- Not tonight, Father. I have a headache.

175
00:19:22,360 --> 00:19:26,273
Let's have "St George, He Was
for England" or "Bobbing Joan".

176
00:19:26,400 --> 00:19:28,630
That's a good song for tonight, eh?

177
00:19:30,160 --> 00:19:33,038
None of your old Handel now,
my little darling.

178
00:19:37,160 --> 00:19:39,276
Ah, you play like an angel.

179
00:19:56,160 --> 00:20:01,473
<i>Molly's reputation was destroyed,
and Tom's heart was heavy with remorse.</i>

180
00:20:01,600 --> 00:20:03,670
<i>Perhaps Mr Square had been right,</i>

181
00:20:03,800 --> 00:20:07,873
<i>that the wicked are snared
in the work of their own hands.</i>

182
00:20:18,840 --> 00:20:21,070
Oh. Mr Jones.

183
00:20:21,200 --> 00:20:24,272
- Where's Molly?
- Oh, she... she ain't home.

184
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:27,753
She's upstairs. In bed.

185
00:20:39,440 --> 00:20:42,113
- Who is it?
- It's me. Tom.

186
00:20:43,360 --> 00:20:45,669
Why haven't you been
to see me before this, Tom?

187
00:20:45,800 --> 00:20:47,995
- Molly, I...
- Agh!

188
00:20:48,120 --> 00:20:51,669
- You said you'd be my gentleman!
- I hope to explain why...

189
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:54,712
You'll not admit you've had
your wicked will of me?!

190
00:20:54,840 --> 00:20:56,068
- Molly...
- No.

191
00:20:56,200 --> 00:20:59,033
I shall never love
another man but you, Tom.

192
00:20:59,520 --> 00:21:02,353
Not if the greatest squire in the country
came a-courtin',

193
00:21:02,480 --> 00:21:04,391
I couldn't give myself to him!

194
00:21:04,520 --> 00:21:10,629
No, Tom, not for all the riches in the
world, now that you've gained my heart.

195
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:15,312
You are a lecherous rascal after all, Tom!

196
00:21:15,440 --> 00:21:20,116
I shall always hate and despise
the whole sex on account of you, Tom!

197
00:21:20,240 --> 00:21:22,196
<i>Mr Square.</i>

198
00:21:23,680 --> 00:21:28,196
<i>Molly's favours, after all,
had not been bestowed on Tom alone.</i>

199
00:21:28,880 --> 00:21:31,519
<i>Our hero, unlike many other men,</i>

200
00:21:31,640 --> 00:21:35,758
<i>was fortunate enough to discover
the father of his child in time.</i>

201
00:21:39,400 --> 00:21:41,914
And after everyone's kindness, too.

202
00:21:42,040 --> 00:21:44,918
She has laid the child
at young Mr Jones's door.

203
00:21:45,040 --> 00:21:49,352
All the parish say Mr Allworthy is so angry
with Mr Jones that he won't see him.

204
00:21:49,480 --> 00:21:52,313
To be sure, one can't help
pitying the poor young man.

205
00:21:52,440 --> 00:21:56,399
He's so pretty a gentleman. I should
be sorry to see him turned out-of-doors.

206
00:21:56,520 --> 00:22:00,115
Why do you tell me all this? What concern
have I in what Mr Jones does?

207
00:22:00,240 --> 00:22:04,392
Why, ma'am, I never thought it was any
harm to say a young man was handsome.

208
00:22:04,520 --> 00:22:08,638
But I shall never think of him any more
now. For handsome is as handsome does.

209
00:22:08,760 --> 00:22:11,957
Tittle-tattle, tittle-tattle.
I shall be late for the hunt.

210
00:22:12,080 --> 00:22:14,275
Sorry, I'm sure, madam.

211
00:22:17,280 --> 00:22:20,431
Everyone in my household!
Where's the cider?

212
00:22:22,360 --> 00:22:24,316
Greetings! Greetings!

213
00:22:25,480 --> 00:22:29,393
- Greetings, Thwackum.
- Morning, Squire. Morning, Miss Western.

214
00:22:31,640 --> 00:22:33,676
Welcome, everyone.

215
00:22:33,800 --> 00:22:35,756
Morning, Western.

216
00:22:38,200 --> 00:22:40,236
Oh, you brute!

217
00:22:42,200 --> 00:22:44,111
- Morning.
- And you, sir.

218
00:22:45,920 --> 00:22:49,549
Ah, you're getting no younger.
I mean the horse, madam.

219
00:22:50,520 --> 00:22:52,511
A stirrup cup, everyone!

220
00:22:53,840 --> 00:22:57,879
Come, help yourselves, everyone!
Plenty to eat and drink!

221
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:01,276
Here. The Church is always first
with the bread and wine.

222
00:23:01,400 --> 00:23:03,356
Health to everyone!

223
00:23:09,480 --> 00:23:12,074
French miss isn't speaking today?

224
00:23:12,200 --> 00:23:14,156
Drink up, everyone.

225
00:23:14,840 --> 00:23:18,276
- Huntsmen, loose the hounds.
- Another tankard, please.

226
00:23:27,160 --> 00:23:30,835
Come on, boys and girls!
Come on, come on!

227
00:23:36,440 --> 00:23:40,752
Have a drop of cider inside you, boy.
Then you'll be ready for the kill.

228
00:23:40,880 --> 00:23:43,553
Come on, drink up. Drink up, everyone.

229
00:23:43,680 --> 00:23:47,912
Come on, drink up!
Some Western brew for you, my girl!

230
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:53,152
Squire, it's too early! You'll tire yourself!

231
00:23:54,840 --> 00:23:58,389
Quiet, everyone.
Good health and good hunting!

232
00:26:59,440 --> 00:27:02,193
Come on, Sophie! Hurry, hurry!

233
00:27:02,680 --> 00:27:05,638
<i>Come on, sweetheart! After him!</i>

234
00:27:12,160 --> 00:27:13,673
Tally-ho!

235
00:27:35,320 --> 00:27:37,754
Ahhh! Here he is!

236
00:28:18,720 --> 00:28:22,872
- I trust you're not harmed.
- No, no. How can I ever thank you?

237
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:26,390
If I have preserved you, madam,
I am sufficiently repaid. Agh...

238
00:28:26,520 --> 00:28:28,351
I hope you're not hurt.

239
00:28:28,480 --> 00:28:32,758
If I have broken my arm, it is a trifle
compared to my fears on your account.

240
00:28:32,880 --> 00:28:34,871
Broken your arm?!

241
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:39,039
I'm afraid I have, madam.
Yet I have another to lead you home.

242
00:28:46,200 --> 00:28:49,829
Look at him, ma'am. He's the most
handsome man I ever saw in my life.

243
00:28:49,960 --> 00:28:52,428
Why, Honor, I do believe
you're in love with him.

244
00:28:52,560 --> 00:28:54,118
I assure you, ma'am, I'm not.

245
00:28:54,240 --> 00:28:57,596
If you were, I see no reason
that you should be ashamed of it.

246
00:28:57,720 --> 00:28:59,597
For he is certainly a handsome fellow.

247
00:28:59,720 --> 00:29:02,917
That he is - the most handsome man
I ever saw in my life.

248
00:29:03,040 --> 00:29:06,669
And, as you say, ma'am, I don't know why
I should be ashamed of looking at him,

249
00:29:06,800 --> 00:29:08,358
even though he is my better.

250
00:29:08,480 --> 00:29:11,597
For gentlefolk are but flesh and blood,
like us servants.

251
00:29:11,720 --> 00:29:15,474
I am an honest person's child,
and my mother and father were married -

252
00:29:15,600 --> 00:29:17,875
<i>which is more than some people can say.</i>

253
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:18,876
Honor!

254
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:21,912
My grandfather was a clergyman,
and he'd have been very angry

255
00:29:22,040 --> 00:29:26,318
to have thought any of his family had
taken up with Molly Seagrim's leavings.

256
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:29,673
Why, ma'am,
the young gentleman is awake.

257
00:29:30,440 --> 00:29:33,159
Yes. You've awakened him
with your foolish chatter.

258
00:29:33,280 --> 00:29:36,238
I feel awake for the first time, madam.

259
00:31:11,080 --> 00:31:15,073
"... after narrow scru...
narrow scrutiny,

260
00:31:15,600 --> 00:31:18,876
found some magical books... " Ha-haar!

261
00:31:20,200 --> 00:31:24,557
